Introduction\
\
Data cubes are a powerful representation of multidimensional data used in OLAP (Online Analytical Processing). They allow businesses to analyze large datasets efficiently.\
\
What is a Data Cube?\
\
A data cube organizes data into multiple dimensions, enabling fast retrieval and aggregation. Each dimension represents a different aspect of the data (e.g., time, location, product).\
\
Example of a Data Cube\
\
Imagine a company analyzing sales based on:\
	\'95	Time (Year, Month, Day)\
	\'95	Location (Country, State, City)\
	\'95	Product (Category, Brand, Model)\
\
A data cube allows users to view sales at different levels, such as total annual sales or monthly sales for a specific region.\
\
Key Operations on Data Cubes\
	1.	Roll-up: Summarizes data (e.g., store-level sales \uc0\u8594  regional sales).\
	2.	Drill-down: Zooms into details (e.g., yearly sales \uc0\u8594  quarterly sales).\
	3.	Slice: Extracts data for a specific dimension (e.g., sales for 2023).\
	4.	Dice: Filters multiple dimensions (e.g., sales for 2023 in New York).\
\
Conclusion\
\
Data cubes enhance query performance and allow users to analyze data in multiple dimensions. They are essential for businesses that rely on large-scale analytics.\
